//1.8 One of the world’s most common objects is a wrist watch. Discuss how each of the following terms and concepts applies to the notion of a watch: object, attributes, behaviors, class, inheritance (consider, for example, an alarm clock), modeling, messages, encapsulation, interface and information hiding.
//Object: A wristwatch is an object that has attributes and behaviors.
//Attributes: Color, brand, material, size, and type (analog/digital).
//Behaviors: Displaying time, setting alarms, showing date, stopwatch functionality.
//Class: A general blueprint for wristwatches defining common attributes and behaviors.
//Inheritance: An alarm clock is a subclass of a wristwatch, inheriting basic features and adding new ones like alarm functionality.
//Modeling: Representing wristwatch features using object-oriented programming.
//Messages: The watch reacts to user inputs (e.g., button presses to adjust time).
//Encapsulation: Internal mechanisms (like time-keeping circuits) are hidden from users.
//Interface: Buttons and dials provide a way to interact with the watch.
//Information Hiding: Users cannot directly modify the internal clock mechanism, only through controlled inputs.

